45-year-old male presents with acute onset chest pain radiating to left arm x 2 hours, started at 1430 while at work. History of hypertension, diabetes type 2, 20 pack-year smoking history. Takes metformin and lisinopril. Patient appears diaphoretic and anxious. Vitals: BP 165/95, HR 105, SpO2 97%, temp 98.6.

EKG obtained at 1455 shows sinus tachycardia, no ST elevation, nonspecific T-wave changes in V3-V5. Troponin initial 0.08 (normal <0.04), repeat at 1615 trending to 0.15. CBC unremarkable. BMP: glucose 245, creatinine 1.1, potassium 4.2. BNP 89. Chest X-ray shows no acute findings, mild cardiomegaly.

Gave aspirin 324mg PO, started heparin drip per ACS protocol at 1510. IV morphine 4mg given at 1525 for persistent chest pain — patient reports improvement from 8/10 to 4/10. Nitroglycerin sublingual x1 given.

Spoke with Dr. Martinez, cardiology on call, at 1545. She recommended continuing heparin, serial troponins, and admission to telemetry for NSTEMI workup. She will see patient in the morning for possible cath.

Patient lives alone, no family nearby, relies on public transportation. He expressed concern about missing work. Patient is uninsured.

Disposition: admit to telemetry for cardiac monitoring and serial troponins.
